{"title_page": "Yellow-throated honeyeater", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Yellow-throated honeyeater\n| image = Lichenostomus flavicollis - Peter Murrel.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704073/0 |title=''Lichenostomus flavicollis'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Nesoptilotis\n| species = flavicollis\n| authority = ([[Louis Jean Pierre Vieillot|Vieillot]], 1817)\n| synonyms = ''Lichenostomus flavicollis''}}\n\nThe '''yellow-throated honeyeater''' (''Nesoptilotis flavicollis'') is a species of [[passerine]] bird in the honeyeater family [[Meliphagidae]]. It is similar in behaviour and appearance to the [[white-eared honeyeater]] and is [[endemic]] to [[Australia|Australia's]] island state of [[Tasmania]]. It was formerly considered a pest of orchards.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\" />\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe species was originally described by French ornithologist Louis Jean Pierre Vieillot in 1817,<ref name=IUCN/> who placed it in the genus ''[[Melithreptus]]''. Its specific epithet is derived from the [[Latin]] words ''flavus'' 'yellow', and ''collis'' 'neck'. Other vernacular names are the green cherry-picker, green dick or green linnet.\n\nThe yellow-throated honeyeater was previously placed in the genus ''[[Lichenostomus]]'', but was moved to ''[[Nesoptilotis]]'' after a [[molecular phylogenetic]] analysis, published in 2011, showed that the original genus was [[polyphyly|polyphyletic]].<ref name=\"Nyari\">{{cite journal | last=Ny\u00e1ri | first=\u00c1.S. | last2=Joseph | first2=L. | year= 2011 |title= Systematic dismantlement of ''Lichenostomus'' improves the basis for understanding relationships within the honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) and historical development of Australo\u2013Papuan bird communities |journal= Emu | volume= 111 |issue= | pages=202\u2013211 | url= |doi=10.1071/mu10047}}</ref><ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | title=Honeyeaters | work= World Bird List Version 6.1 | url= http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/honeyeaters/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union| accessdate= 28 January 2016 }}</ref>  It is a sister taxon to the [[white-eared honeyeater]] (''N. leucotis''), which occurs on mainland Australia but not in Tasmania, and they belong to a clade that contains the genera ''[[Entomyzon]]'', ''[[Melithreptus]]'' and ''[[Foulehaio]]''.<ref name=Nyari/>\n\n==Description==\nThe yellow-throated honeyeater is a medium-sized honeyeater with a relatively long tail. Typical weight is {{convert|31|g|oz|abbr=on}} and the average length is {{convert|21|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\"/> The [[plumage]] is bright olive-green above, with a silver-grey crown, face, and underbelly, contrasting with a distinctive bright yellow chin and throat. There is a small yellow ear-patch and the wing feathers are outlined with yellow. The bill is black and the eye is a deep ruby red. Females are smaller than males. Juvenile birds are very similar to adults, but duller.\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe yellow-throated honeyeater is common and widespread on the mainland of Tasmania, [[King Island (Tasmania)|King Island]] and the [[Furneaux Group]].<ref name=\"pizzey\">{{cite book |title=Field Guide to the Birds of Australia |last=Pizzey |first=Graham |author2=Knight, Frank  |year=1997 |publisher=HarperCollinsPublishers |location=Sydney, Australia |isbn=0-207-18013-X |page=111}}</ref> It is not considered [[threatened]].\n\nIts natural [[habitat]] is temperate [[forest]]s, [[woodland]]s, and coastal scrub and heath.<ref name=\"pizzey\" /> Both wet and dry [[sclerophyll]] forests are the preferred habitats, with other habitats like alpine eucalypt woodland and open eucalypt woodland, cool rainforest, coastal heathlands, and shrublands also being used.<ref name =\"HBW\"/>  They may also be found in golf courses, orchards, parks and gardens.<ref name=\"pizzey\" /> Older stands of dry [[sclerophyll]] may be adversely affected by fire.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\"/>\n\n==Behaviour==\n[[File:Lichenostomus flavicollis - Peter Murrel.ogv|thumb|A yellow-throated honeyeater calling]]\nThe yellow-throated honeyeater is territorial and quite aggressive towards other honeyeaters, [[pardalote]]s, [[golden whistler]]s, and [[grey shrike-thrush]]es, and will chase them away from their territories.\n\n===Feeding===\n\nThe yellow-throated honeyeater feeds mainly on [[arthropod]]s,<ref name = \"HBW\">{{Cite book | first = PJ | last = Higgins | first2 = L| last2 = Christidis | first3 = HA | last3 = Ford | editor-last = Josep | editor-first = del Hoyo | editor2-last = Andrew | editor2-first = Elliott | editor3-last = David | editor3-first = Christie | contribution = Family Meliphagidae (Honeyeaters) | title = [[Handbook of the Birds of the World]]. Volume 13, Penduline-tits to Shrikes | year = 2008 | pages = 605\u2013606 | place = Barcelona | publisher = Lynx Edicions | isbn = 978-84-96553-45-3 }}</ref> also taking some nectar,<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\" /> and occasionally fruit or seeds.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\" /> The species forages from the canopy down to the ground, usually singly or in pairs. Food is obtained by gleaning from trunks, branches, and the ground, by probing between loose bark on the trunks, and by occasional sallying flights. More rarely flowers are investigated for insects or nectar.<ref name = \"HBW\"/>\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Lichenostomus flavicollis stealing hair from Thylogale billardierii for nest - Melaleuca.jpg|thumb|left|A yellow-throated honeyeater taking hair from a live [[Tasmanian pademelon]] for nesting material, [[Melaleuca, Tasmania|Melaleuca]], Southwest Conservation Area, Tasmania, Australia]]\nBreeding occurs from August to January. During breeding season females move into male territories.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\" /> The nest is often within 1&nbsp;m of the ground in a low bush or tussock, but may occasionally be found at up to 10&nbsp;m in foliage. It is constructed by the female from grass, bark-shreds, leaves and spiders' web and lined with treefern fibres, wool, and fur.<ref name=\"pizzey\" /> This species is known for collecting hair for the nest from live animals, such as horses, dogs, and humans.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\">[http://www.birdsinbackyards.net/finder/display.cfm?id=290 Birds in Backyards \u2013 Yellow-throated Honeyeater]</ref> The female incubates the eggs and feeds the young.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\" /> A typical clutch is two or three<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\"/><ref name=\"pizzey\" /> pinkish eggs,<ref name=\"pws\">[http://www.parks.tas.gov.au/index.aspx?base=5189 Parks & Wildlife Service \u2013 Yellow-Throated Honeyeater]</ref> and the incubation period is approximately 16 days.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\"/> The female alone incubates the eggs, and also feeds the nestlings.<ref name =\"HBW\"/> Hatchlings also spend around 16 days in the nest.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\"/> The male will drive off the fledglings and the female when they are old enough to disperse (usually at around three weeks).<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\" /> This species is [[brood parasitism|parasitised]] by the [[fan-tailed cuckoo]] and the [[pallid cuckoo]].<ref name =\"HBW\"/>\n\n===Calls===\n\nThe yellow-throated honeyeater makes a variety of [[bird vocalization|calls]]. These include a breeding call, used for attracting mates, and to advertise ownership of a territory. That call varies geographically, but essentially consists of a whirring ''chur-uk, chur-uk'' or a loud ''de-wit'', and is used during breeding season.<ref>[http://www.publish.csiro.au/paper/MU9880065.htm CSIRO Publishing \u2013 Spatial and Individual Variation in the Songs of the Yellow-throated Honeyeater Lichenostomus flavicollis Abstract]</ref>\nAnother common call is a repeated ''tonk, tonk, tonk'' or ''tchook, tchook''. \n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Nesoptilotis flavicollis}}\n{{Wikispecies|Lichenostomus flavicollis}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1314908}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:honeyeater, yellow-throated}}\n[[Category:Nesoptilotis|yellow-throated honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1817|yellow-throated honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Yellow-throated honeyeater\n| image = Lichenostomus flavicollis - Peter Murrel.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22704073/0 |title=''Lichenostomus flavicollis'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Nesoptilotis\n| species = flavicollis\n| authority = ([[Louis Jean Pierre Vieillot|Vieillot]], 1817)\n| synonyms = ''Lichenostomus flavicollis''}}\n\nThe '''yellow-throated honeyeater''' (''Nesoptilotis flavicollis'') is a species of [[passerine]] bird in the honeyeater family [[Meliphagidae]]. It is similar in behaviour and appearance to the [[white-eared honeyeater]] and is [[endemic]] to [[Australia|Australia's]] island state of [[Tasmania]]. It was formerly considered a pest of orchards.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\" />\n\n==Taxonomy==\nThe species was originally described by French ornithologist Louis Jean Pierre Vieillot in 1817,<ref name=IUCN/> who placed it in the genus ''[[Melithreptus]]''. Its specific epithet is derived from the [[Latin]] words ''flavus'' 'yellow', and ''collis'' 'neck'. Other vernacular names are the green cherry-picker, green dick or green linnet.\n\nThe yellow-throated honeyeater was previously placed in the genus ''[[Lichenostomus]]'', but was moved to ''[[Nesoptilotis]]'' after a [[molecular phylogenetic]] analysis, published in 2011, showed that the original genus was [[polyphyly|polyphyletic]].<ref name=\"Nyari\">{{cite journal | last=Ny\u00e1ri | first=\u00c1.S. | last2=Joseph | first2=L. | year= 2011 |title= Systematic dismantlement of ''Lichenostomus'' improves the basis for understanding relationships within the honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) and historical development of Australo\u2013Papuan bird communities |journal= Emu | volume= 111 |issue= | pages=202\u2013211 | url= |doi=10.1071/mu10047}}</ref><ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | title=Honeyeaters | work= World Bird List Version 6.1 | url= http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/honeyeaters/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union| accessdate= 28 January 2016 }}</ref>  It is a sister taxon to the [[white-eared honeyeater]] (''N. leucotis''), which occurs on mainland Australia, but not in Tasmania, and they belong to a clade that contains the genera ''[[Entomyzon]]'', ''[[Melithreptus]]'' and ''[[Foulehaio]]''.<ref name=Nyari/>\n\n==Description==\nThe yellow-throated honeyeater is a medium-sized honeyeater with a relatively long tail. Typical weight is {{convert|31|g|oz|abbr=on}} and the average length is {{convert|21|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\"/> The [[plumage]] is bright olive-green above, with a silver-grey crown, face, and underbelly, contrasting with a distinctive bright yellow chin and throat. There is a small yellow ear-patch and the wing feathers are outlined with yellow. The bill is black and the eye is a deep ruby red. Females are smaller than males. Juvenile birds are very similar to adults, but duller.\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThe yellow-throated honeyeater is common and widespread on the mainland of Tasmania, [[King Island (Tasmania)|King Island]] and the [[Furneaux Group]].<ref name=\"pizzey\">{{cite book |title=Field Guide to the Birds of Australia |last=Pizzey |first=Graham |author2=Knight, Frank  |year=1997 |publisher=HarperCollinsPublishers |location=Sydney, Australia |isbn=0-207-18013-X |page=111}}</ref> It is not considered [[threatened]].\n\nIts natural [[habitat]] is temperate [[forest]]s, [[woodland]]s, and coastal scrub and heath.<ref name=\"pizzey\" /> Both wet and dry [[sclerophyll]] forests are the preferred habitats, with other habitats like alpine eucalypt woodland and open eucalypt woodland, cool rainforest, coastal heathlands, and shrublands also being used.<ref name =\"HBW\"/>  They may also be found in golf courses, orchards, parks and gardens.<ref name=\"pizzey\" /> Older stands of dry [[sclerophyll]] may be adversely affected by fire.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\"/>\n\n==Behaviour==\n[[File:Lichenostomus flavicollis - Peter Murrel.ogv|thumb|A yellow-throated honeyeater calling]]\nThe yellow-throated honeyeater is territorial and quite aggressive towards other honeyeaters, [[pardalote]]s, [[golden whistler]]s, and [[grey shrike-thrush]]es, and will chase them away from their territories.\n\n===Feeding===\n\nThe yellow-throated honeyeater feeds mainly on [[arthropod]]s,<ref name = \"HBW\">{{Cite book | first = PJ | last = Higgins | first2 = L| last2 = Christidis | first3 = HA | last3 = Ford | editor-last = Josep | editor-first = del Hoyo | editor2-last = Andrew | editor2-first = Elliott | editor3-last = David | editor3-first = Christie | contribution = Family Meliphagidae (Honeyeaters) | title = [[Handbook of the Birds of the World]]. Volume 13, Penduline-tits to Shrikes | year = 2008 | pages = 605\u2013606 | place = Barcelona | publisher = Lynx Edicions | isbn = 978-84-96553-45-3 }}</ref> also taking some nectar,<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\" /> and occasionally fruit or seeds.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\" /> The species forages from the canopy down to the ground, usually singly or in pairs. Food is obtained by gleaning from trunks, branches, and the ground, by probing between loose bark on the trunks, and by occasional sallying flights. More rarely flowers are investigated for insects or nectar.<ref name = \"HBW\"/>\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Lichenostomus flavicollis stealing hair from Thylogale billardierii for nest - Melaleuca.jpg|thumb|left|A yellow-throated honeyeater taking hair from a live [[Tasmanian pademelon]] for nesting material, [[Melaleuca, Tasmania|Melaleuca]], Southwest Conservation Area, Tasmania, Australia]]\nBreeding occurs from August to January. During breeding season females move into male territories.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\" /> The nest is often within 1&nbsp;m of the ground in a low bush or tussock, but may occasionally be found at up to 10&nbsp;m in foliage. It is constructed by the female from grass, bark-shreds, leaves and spiders' web and lined with treefern fibres, wool, and fur.<ref name=\"pizzey\" /> This species is known for collecting hair for the nest from live animals, such as horses, dogs, and humans.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\">[http://www.birdsinbackyards.net/finder/display.cfm?id=290 Birds in Backyards \u2013 Yellow-throated Honeyeater]</ref> The female incubates the eggs and feeds the young.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\" /> A typical clutch is two or three<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\"/><ref name=\"pizzey\" /> pinkish eggs,<ref name=\"pws\">[http://www.parks.tas.gov.au/index.aspx?base=5189 Parks & Wildlife Service \u2013 Yellow-Throated Honeyeater]</ref> and the incubation period is approximately 16 days.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\"/> The female alone incubates the eggs, and also feeds the nestlings.<ref name =\"HBW\"/> Hatchlings also spend around 16 days in the nest.<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\"/> The male will drive off the fledglings and the female when they are old enough to disperse (usually at around three weeks).<ref name=\"birdsinbackyards\" /> This species is [[brood parasitism|parasitised]] by the [[fan-tailed cuckoo]] and the [[pallid cuckoo]].<ref name =\"HBW\"/>\n\n===Calls===\n\nThe yellow-throated honeyeater makes a variety of [[bird vocalization|calls]]. These include a breeding call, used for attracting mates, and to advertise ownership of a territory. That call varies geographically, but essentially consists of a whirring ''chur-uk, chur-uk'' or a loud ''de-wit'', and is used during breeding season.<ref>[http://www.publish.csiro.au/paper/MU9880065.htm CSIRO Publishing \u2013 Spatial and Individual Variation in the Songs of the Yellow-throated Honeyeater Lichenostomus flavicollis Abstract]</ref>\nAnother common call is a repeated ''tonk, tonk, tonk'' or ''tchook, tchook''. \n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Nesoptilotis flavicollis}}\n{{Wikispecies|Lichenostomus flavicollis}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1314908}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:honeyeater, yellow-throated}}\n[[Category:Nesoptilotis|yellow-throated honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1817|yellow-throated honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTaxonomy:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yellow-throated_honeyeater"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saint Lucia", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Saint Lucia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saint Lucia\n| map1            = File:Saint Lucia map.gif\n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Saint Lucia]]\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = 13 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=13|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| first_outbreak  = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| confirmed_cases = 15<ref name=\"loop-24april\">{{cite web |url=https://www.loopslu.com/content/st-lucia-will-likely-record-new-covid-19-cases-health-ministry |title=St Lucia will likely record new COVID-19 cases - Health Ministry |date=2020-04-24 |work=Loop News}}</ref> (2020-04-24)\n| recovery_cases  = 15<ref name=\"loop-24april\" />\n| deaths          = 0<ref name=\"loop-24april\" />\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]] in Saint Lucia''' is part of the ongoing global [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|viral pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), which was confirmed to have reached [[Saint Lucia]] on 13 March 2020.<ref name=\"Case_1\"/> As of 22 April, there have been 15 confirmed cases, all of whom have recovered.<ref name=\"loop-22april\"/>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{Medical cases chart\n|numwidth=wmd\n\n|disease=COVID-19\n|location=Saint Lucia\n|outbreak=2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic\n\n<!-- |togglesbar=\n<div class=\"nomobile\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n{{Medical cases chart/Month toggle button|mar}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Month toggle button|apr}}\n<span class=\"mw-collapsible mw-customtoggle-l15 mw-customtoggle-mar-l15 mw-customtoggle-apr-l15 mw-collapsed\" id=\"mw-customcollapsible-l15\" style=\"padding:0 8px\">Last 15 days</span>\n<span class=\"mw-collapsible mw-customtoggle-l15 mw-customtoggle-mar-l15 mw-customtoggle-apr-l15\" id=\"mw-customcollapsible-l15\" style=\"border:2px solid lightblue; padding:0 8px\">Last 15 days</span>\n</div> -->\n\n|data=\n<!--date;deaths;recoveries;total_cases;;;total_cases;+%;-->\n2020-03-13; 0;  0;  1;;;  1;\n2020-03-14; 0;  0;  2;;;  2;+100%\n;            ;  0;  2;;;  2;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-23; 0;  0;  3;;;  3;+50%\n;            ;  0;  3;;;  3;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-26; 0;  1;  3;;;  3;=\n;            ;  1;  3;;;  3;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-29; 0;  1;  9;;;  9;+200%\n2020-03-30; 0;  1;  9;;;  9;=\n2020-03-31; 0;  1; 13;;; 13;+44%\n;            ;  1; 13;;; 13;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-04-04; 0;  1; 14;;; 14;+7.7%\n;            ;  1; 14;;; 14;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-04-10; 0;  1; 15;;; 15;+7.1%\n2020-04-11; 0;  1; 15;;; 15;=\n2020-04-12; 0;  4; 15;;; 15;=\n2020-04-13; 0;  4; 15;;; 15;=\n2020-04-14; 0; 11; 15;;; 15;=\n;            ; 11; 15;;; 15;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-04-20; 0; 13; 15;;; 15;=\n2020-04-21; 0; 14; 15;;; 15;=\n2020-04-22; 0; 15; 15;;; 15;=\n\n|caption=Data sourced from [https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/saint-lucia/ Worldometers Saint Lucia] and references in this document.\n}}\n=== March 2020 ===\nOn 13 March 2020, the first case in [[Saint Lucia]] was confirmed.<ref name=\"Case_1\">{{Cite web |url=https://stluciatimes.com/uk-national-is-saint-lucias-first-coronavirus-case/ |title=UK National Is Saint Lucia's First Coronavirus Case |date=11 March 2020 |work=St. Lucia Times}}</ref> The patient is a 63-year-old woman with a travel history from the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"Case_1b\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/st-lucia-confirms-its-first-covid-19-case-woman-63-with-uk-travel-history/ |title=St. Lucia confirms its first COVID-19 case: woman, 63, with UK travel history |date=11 March 2020 |work=St. Lucia News Online}}</ref> The Department of Health and Wellness confirmed a second case on 14 March 2020.<ref name=\"Case_2\">{{Cite press release |title=BREAKING NEWS: Saint Lucia confirms its second COVID-19 case |publisher=Department of Health and Wellness |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-saint-lucia-confirms-its-second-covid-19-case/ |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> The patients were repatriated to the United Kingdom on 24 and 25 March.<ref name=\"Ministry 25 March\">{{Cite press release |title=Saint Lucia's only coronavirus patient \"has recovered\"; two other patients repatriated |publisher=Ministry of Health and Wellness |date=25 March 2020 |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/saint-lucias-only-coronavirus-patient-has-recovered-two-other-patients-repatriated/?recaptcha-opt-in=true |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, Prime Minister [[Allen Chastanet]] announced that Saint Lucia would implement [[social distancing]] measures, including the suspension of nonessential commercial activity from 23 March through 5 April.<ref name=\"nonessential\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.loopslu.com/content/st-lucia-closing-non-essential-commercial-services-2-weeks |title=St Lucia closing non-essential commercial services for 2 weeks |work=Loop News |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> The government also imposed a 11 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew. On 29 March, the Prime Minister extended the shutdown to 14 April and extended the curfew to 8 p.m. to 5 a.m.<ref name=\"29 March curfew\">{{Cite press release |title=Prime Minister extends quarantine, increases curfew |publisher=Government Information Service |date=30 March 2020 |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/prime-minister-extends-quarantine-increases-curfew/ |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.loopslu.com/content/breaking-news-saint-lucia-curfew-hours-extended-april-14 |title=St Lucia extends curfew due to uncooperative public; COVID-19 spread |publisher=Loop News |author=Sharefil Gaillard |date=29 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March 2020, the Government of Saint Lucia declared a state of emergency and announced the closure of the country's airports to incoming passenger flights until 5 April.<ref name=\"Case_3b\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-saint-lucia-declares-state-of-emergency/ |title=BREAKING NEWS: Saint Lucia declares state of emergency |publisher=St. Lucia News Online |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release |title=BREAKING NEWS: St. Lucia airports closed to arriving passengers |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-st-lucia-airports-closed-to-arriving-passengers/  |publisher=Office of the Prime Minister |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March 2020, the Ministry of Health began local testing for COVID-19 and, on 29 March, it reported the first instance of local transmission among six new confirmed cases.  The ministry also reported that 300 persons were under supervised quarantine.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Saint Lucia's 4th COVID-19 victim 'doing well'; over 300 in quarantine |publisher=Ministry of Health and Wellness |date=28 March 2020 |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-st-lucia-records-4th-coronavirus-case-first-positive-case-from-local-testing/ |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Ministry 30 March\">{{Cite press release |title=Saint Lucia now experiencing local transmission of COVID-19 |publisher=Ministry of Health |date=30 March 2020 |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/saint-lucia-now-experiencing-local-transmission-of-covid-19/ |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March 2020, all restaurants, bars, and liquor licences were to close. <ref name=\"liquor\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/lifting-covid-19-liquor-ban-st-lucia-being-considered-0|title=Lifting of COVID-19 liquor ban in St Lucia being considered |website=Loopnews Barbados|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March 2020, the Prime Minister announced a 24-hour curfew confining all persons to their place of residence from 5 a.m. 1 April to 5 a.m. 7 April.<ref name=\"Curfew 31 March\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-saint-lucia-govt-implements-24-hour-curfew/ |title=BREAKING NEWS: Saint Lucia gov't implements 24-hour curfew |publisher=St. Lucia News Online |date=31 March 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> At the time of the announcement, persons were already under curfew meaning they could not make any arrangements for the new curfew.<ref name=\"Social distancing\" />\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nOn 1 April 2020, the Prime Minister announced that mini-marts and bakeries would be open for a limited time to allow people to buy goods.<ref name=\"Shops open on limited basis\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.loopslu.com/content/pm-mini-marts-bakeries-open-april-2-and-6-minimal-farming-allowed |title=PM: Mini marts, bakeries open April 2 and 6; minimal farming allowed |publisher=Loop News |date=1 April 2020 |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> On 2 April, St. Lucians queued up in long lines outside the briefly opened shops, mostly ignoring the prime minister's calls to practise social distancing.<ref name=\"Social distancing\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.loopslu.com/content/st-lucians-again-fail-social-distancing-during-curfew-shopping |title=St Lucians again fail at social distancing during curfew shopping |publisher=Loop News |author=Jonathan Stuart |date=2 April 2020 |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2020, the Prime Minister announced that St. Lucia would revert to a 10-hour 7 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew from 7 April through 13 April. Essential businesses would be allowed to operate from 7 a.m. to 4 p.m., except during the Good Friday, Easter and Easter Monday holidays.<ref name=\"ten_hour_curfew\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.loopslu.com/content/pm-announces-no-shopping-monday-10-hour-curfew-begins-tuesday |title=PM announces no shopping Monday; 10-hour curfew begins Tuesday |publisher=Loop News |author=Jonathan Stuart |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 April 2020, the government extended the 10-hour 7 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew and partial commercial shutdown through 26 April. The government added hardware and home supply stores to the list of businesses permitted to operate to allow preparation for the drought and hurricane seasons.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Merrick Andrews |title=Chastanet: 10-hour curfew extended to April 26; hardware stores, home suppliers to open |work=St. Lucia News Online |date=12 April 2020 |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/chastanet-10-hour-curfew-stays-in-place-hardware-stores-home-suppliers-to-open/ |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 2020, Chief Medical Officer Dr Sharon Belmar-George announced that all 15 of the country's confirmed cases had recovered, including those at high risk because of their age or preexisting conditions. All measures including the curfew will remain in effect for now, and Belmar-George warned against a resurge in the future.<ref name=\"loop-22april\">{{cite web |url=https://www.loopslu.com/content/all-st-lucias-covid-19-patients-have-now-recovered |title=All of St Lucia's COVID-19 patients have now recovered |date=2020-04-22 |work=Loop News}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Allen Chastanet]] was asked about lifting the alcohol restriction. Chastanet will look in it, but wants to follow the advice by the Chief Medical Officer.<ref name=\"liquor\" />\n<br>\nThe Cabinet of Saint Lucia agreed to cut their salary by 75% due to the economic crisis caused by the coronavirus and the loss of income from tourism. The government will meet on 28 April to deal with the loss of revenue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/regional/st-lucia-cabinet-agrees-to-75-per-cent-salary-cut-in-face-of-economic-crisis|title=St. Lucia Cabinet agrees to 75 per cent salary cut in face of economic crisis |website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 April 2020, the Ministy of Health announced: \"Though this 100 percent recovery rate provides us with a milestone worth recognizing, we at the Ministry of Health continue to caution the public that any gains attained should not be understood as a reason to let down our guard or to throw caution to the wind.\" Between 21 and 24 April, 60 tests have been performed all resulting negative.<ref name=\"loop-24april\" />\n\n==Preventive measures==\n* All schools are closed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://rcistlucia.com/covid-19-schools-closed/|title=Educational Institutions Closed from Monday 16th, 2020|website=RCI St Lucia|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Non-essential businesses are closed.<ref name=\"nonessential\"/>\n* Curfew between 23:00 and 05:00.<ref name=\"29 March curfew\"/> Changed to 19:00 to 05:00 on 5 April.<ref name=\"ten_hour_curfew\"/>\n* Restaurants and bars are closed. [[Prohibition|Alcohol sales]] prohibited.<ref name=\"liquor\"/>\n* Airports are closed.<ref name=\"Case_3b\"/>\n* Limited reopening of minimarts and bakeries.<ref name=\"Shops open on limited basis\"/>\n\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"> </div>\n\n==Statistics==\nChronology of the number of active cases\n{{Graph:Chart\n| type = line\n| linewidth = 1\n| showSymbols = 1\n| yType= integer\n| width = 600\n| colors = #ff6347, cyan, black\n| xAxisTitle = Date\n| xAxisAngle = -40\n| xType = date\n| xAxisFormat = %e %b\n| x = 12 March 2020, 13 March 2020, 14 March 2020, 15 March 2020, 16 March 2020, 17 March 2020, 18 March 2020, 19 March 2020, 20 March 2020, 21 March 2020, 22 March 2020, 23 March 2020, 24 March 2020, 25 March 2020, 26 March 2020, 27 March 2020, 28 March 2020, 29 March 2020, 30 March 2020, 31 March 2020, \n1 April 2020, 2 April 2020, 3 April 2020, 4 April 2020, 5 April 2020, 6 April 2020, 7 April 2020, 8 April 2020, 9 April 2020, 10 April 2020, 11 April 2020, 12 April 2020, 13 April 2020, 14 April 2020, 15 April 2020, 16 April 2020, 17 April 2020, 18 April 2020, 19 April 2020, 20 April 2020, 21 April 2020, 22 April 2020\n| yAxisTitle = No. of cases\n| y1 = \n0,   1,  2,  2,  2,  2,  2,  2,  2,  2,  2,  3,  3,  3,  2,  2,  2,  8,  8, 12,  <!--          March -->\n12, 12, 12, 13, 13, 13, 13, 13, 13, 14, 14, 11, 11,  4,  4,                      <!-- up to 15 April -->\n4,   4,  4,  4,  2,  1,  0,\n| yGrid = \n| xGrid = \n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Saint Lucia|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Saint Lucia]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Caribbean|Saint Lucia]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Saint Lucia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Saint Lucia}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Saint Lucia\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Saint Lucia]]\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = 13 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=13|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| first_outbreak  = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| confirmed_cases = 15<ref name=\"loop-24april\">{{cite web |url=https://www.loopslu.com/content/st-lucia-will-likely-record-new-covid-19-cases-health-ministry |title=St Lucia will likely record new COVID-19 cases - Health Ministry |date=2020-04-24 |work=Loop News}}</ref> (2020-04-24)\n| recovery_cases  = 15<ref name=\"loop-24april\" />\n| deaths          = 0<ref name=\"loop-24april\" />\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]] in Saint Lucia''' is part of the ongoing global [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|viral pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), which was confirmed to have reached [[Saint Lucia]] on 13 March 2020.<ref name=\"Case_1\"/> As of 22 April, there have been 15 confirmed cases, all of whom have recovered.<ref name=\"loop-22april\"/>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{Medical cases chart\n|numwidth=wmd\n\n|disease=COVID-19\n|location=Saint Lucia\n|outbreak=2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic\n\n<!-- |togglesbar=\n<div class=\"nomobile\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n{{Medical cases chart/Month toggle button|mar}}\n{{Medical cases chart/Month toggle button|apr}}\n<span class=\"mw-collapsible mw-customtoggle-l15 mw-customtoggle-mar-l15 mw-customtoggle-apr-l15 mw-collapsed\" id=\"mw-customcollapsible-l15\" style=\"padding:0 8px\">Last 15 days</span>\n<span class=\"mw-collapsible mw-customtoggle-l15 mw-customtoggle-mar-l15 mw-customtoggle-apr-l15\" id=\"mw-customcollapsible-l15\" style=\"border:2px solid lightblue; padding:0 8px\">Last 15 days</span>\n</div> -->\n\n|data=\n<!--date;deaths;recoveries;total_cases;;;total_cases;+%;-->\n2020-03-13; 0;  0;  1;;;  1;\n2020-03-14; 0;  0;  2;;;  2;+100%\n;            ;  0;  2;;;  2;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-23; 0;  0;  3;;;  3;+50%\n;            ;  0;  3;;;  3;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-26; 0;  1;  3;;;  3;=\n;            ;  1;  3;;;  3;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-03-29; 0;  1;  9;;;  9;+200%\n2020-03-30; 0;  1;  9;;;  9;=\n2020-03-31; 0;  1; 13;;; 13;+44%\n;            ;  1; 13;;; 13;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-04-04; 0;  1; 14;;; 14;+7.7%\n;            ;  1; 14;;; 14;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-04-10; 0;  1; 15;;; 15;+7.1%\n2020-04-11; 0;  1; 15;;; 15;=\n2020-04-12; 0;  4; 15;;; 15;=\n2020-04-13; 0;  4; 15;;; 15;=\n2020-04-14; 0; 11; 15;;; 15;=\n;            ; 11; 15;;; 15;collapsed=y;id=mar\n2020-04-20; 0; 13; 15;;; 15;=\n2020-04-21; 0; 14; 15;;; 15;=\n2020-04-22; 0; 15; 15;;; 15;=\n\n|caption=Data sourced from [https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/saint-lucia/ Worldometers Saint Lucia] and references in this document.\n}}\n=== March 2020 ===\nOn 13 March 2020, the first case in [[Saint Lucia]] was confirmed.<ref name=\"Case_1\">{{Cite web |url=https://stluciatimes.com/uk-national-is-saint-lucias-first-coronavirus-case/ |title=UK National Is Saint Lucia's First Coronavirus Case |date=11 March 2020 |work=St. Lucia Times}}</ref> The patient is a 63-year-old woman with a travel history from the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"Case_1b\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/st-lucia-confirms-its-first-covid-19-case-woman-63-with-uk-travel-history/ |title=St. Lucia confirms its first COVID-19 case: woman, 63, with UK travel history |date=11 March 2020 |work=St. Lucia News Online}}</ref> The Department of Health and Wellness confirmed a second case on 14 March 2020.<ref name=\"Case_2\">{{Cite press release |title=BREAKING NEWS: Saint Lucia confirms its second COVID-19 case |publisher=Department of Health and Wellness |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-saint-lucia-confirms-its-second-covid-19-case/ |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> The patients were repatriated to the United Kingdom on 24 and 25 March.<ref name=\"Ministry 25 March\">{{Cite press release |title=Saint Lucia's only coronavirus patient \"has recovered\"; two other patients repatriated |publisher=Ministry of Health and Wellness |date=25 March 2020 |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/saint-lucias-only-coronavirus-patient-has-recovered-two-other-patients-repatriated/?recaptcha-opt-in=true |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March 2020, Prime Minister [[Allen Chastanet]] announced that Saint Lucia would implement [[social distancing]] measures, including the suspension of nonessential commercial activity from 23 March through 5 April.<ref name=\"nonessential\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.loopslu.com/content/st-lucia-closing-non-essential-commercial-services-2-weeks |title=St Lucia closing non-essential commercial services for 2 weeks |work=Loop News |date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> The government also imposed a 11 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew. On 29 March, the Prime Minister extended the shutdown to 14 April and extended the curfew to 8 p.m. to 5 a.m.<ref name=\"29 March curfew\">{{Cite press release |title=Prime Minister extends quarantine, increases curfew |publisher=Government Information Service |date=30 March 2020 |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/prime-minister-extends-quarantine-increases-curfew/ |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.loopslu.com/content/breaking-news-saint-lucia-curfew-hours-extended-april-14 |title=St Lucia extends curfew due to uncooperative public; COVID-19 spread |publisher=Loop News |author=Sharefil Gaillard |date=29 March 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March 2020, the Government of Saint Lucia declared a state of emergency and announced the closure of the country's airports to incoming passenger flights until 5 April.<ref name=\"Case_3b\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-saint-lucia-declares-state-of-emergency/ |title=BREAKING NEWS: Saint Lucia declares state of emergency |publisher=St. Lucia News Online |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite press release |title=BREAKING NEWS: St. Lucia airports closed to arriving passengers |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-st-lucia-airports-closed-to-arriving-passengers/  |publisher=Office of the Prime Minister |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March 2020, the Ministry of Health began local testing for COVID-19 and, on 29 March, it reported the first instance of local transmission among six new confirmed cases.  The ministry also reported that 300 persons were under supervised quarantine.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Saint Lucia's 4th COVID-19 victim 'doing well'; over 300 in quarantine |publisher=Ministry of Health and Wellness |date=28 March 2020 |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-st-lucia-records-4th-coronavirus-case-first-positive-case-from-local-testing/ |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Ministry 30 March\">{{Cite press release |title=Saint Lucia now experiencing local transmission of COVID-19 |publisher=Ministry of Health |date=30 March 2020 |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/saint-lucia-now-experiencing-local-transmission-of-covid-19/ |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March 2020, all restaurants, bars, and liquor licences were to close. <ref name=\"liquor\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/lifting-covid-19-liquor-ban-st-lucia-being-considered-0|title=Lifting of COVID-19 liquor ban in St Lucia being considered |website=Loopnews Barbados|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March 2020, the Prime Minister announced a 24-hour curfew confining all persons to their place of residence from 5 a.m. 1 April to 5 a.m. 7 April.<ref name=\"Curfew 31 March\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/breaking-news-saint-lucia-govt-implements-24-hour-curfew/ |title=BREAKING NEWS: Saint Lucia gov't implements 24-hour curfew |publisher=St. Lucia News Online |date=31 March 2020 |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> At the time of the announcement, persons were already under curfew meaning they could not make any arrangements for the new curfew.<ref name=\"Social distancing\" />\n\n=== April 2020 ===\nOn 1 April 2020, the Prime Minister announced that mini-marts and bakeries would be open for a limited time to allow people to buy goods.<ref name=\"Shops open on limited basis\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.loopslu.com/content/pm-mini-marts-bakeries-open-april-2-and-6-minimal-farming-allowed |title=PM: Mini marts, bakeries open April 2 and 6; minimal farming allowed |publisher=Loop News |date=1 April 2020 |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref> On 2 April, St. Lucians queued up in long lines outside the briefly opened shops, mostly ignoring the prime minister's calls to practise social distancing.<ref name=\"Social distancing\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.loopslu.com/content/st-lucians-again-fail-social-distancing-during-curfew-shopping |title=St Lucians again fail at social distancing during curfew shopping |publisher=Loop News |author=Jonathan Stuart |date=2 April 2020 |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 2020, the Prime Minister announced that St. Lucia would revert to a 10-hour 7 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew from 7 April through 13 April. Essential businesses would be allowed to operate from 7 a.m. to 4 p.m., except during the Good Friday, Easter and Easter Monday holidays.<ref name=\"ten_hour_curfew\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.loopslu.com/content/pm-announces-no-shopping-monday-10-hour-curfew-begins-tuesday |title=PM announces no shopping Monday; 10-hour curfew begins Tuesday |publisher=Loop News |author=Jonathan Stuart |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 April 2020, the government extended the 10-hour 7 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew and partial commercial shutdown through 26 April. The government added hardware and home supply stores to the list of businesses permitted to operate to allow preparation for the drought and hurricane seasons.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Merrick Andrews |title=Chastanet: 10-hour curfew extended to April 26; hardware stores, home suppliers to open |work=St. Lucia News Online |date=12 April 2020 |url=https://www.stlucianewsonline.com/chastanet-10-hour-curfew-stays-in-place-hardware-stores-home-suppliers-to-open/ |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 April 2020, Chief Medical Officer Dr Sharon Belmar-George announced that all 15 of the country's confirmed cases had recovered, including those at high risk because of their age or preexisting conditions. All measures including the curfew will remain in effect for now, and Belmar-George warned against a resurge in the future.<ref name=\"loop-22april\">{{cite web |url=https://www.loopslu.com/content/all-st-lucias-covid-19-patients-have-now-recovered |title=All of St Lucia's COVID-19 patients have now recovered |date=2020-04-22 |work=Loop News}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Allen Chastanet]] was asked about lifting the alcohol restriction. Chastanet will look in it, but wants to follow the advice by the Chief Medical Officer.<ref name=\"liquor\" />\n<br>\nThe Cabinet of Saint Lucia agreed to cut their salary by 75% due to the economic crisis caused by the coronavirus and the loss of income from tourism. The government will meet on 28 April to deal with the loss of revenue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailyherald.sx/regional/st-lucia-cabinet-agrees-to-75-per-cent-salary-cut-in-face-of-economic-crisis|title=St. Lucia Cabinet agrees to 75 per cent salary cut in face of economic crisis |website=The Daily Herald.sx|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 April 2020, the Ministy of Health announced: \"Though this 100 percent recovery rate provides us with a milestone worth recognizing, we at the Ministry of Health continue to caution the public that any gains attained should not be understood as a reason to let down our guard or to throw caution to the wind.\" Between 21 and 24 April, 60 tests have been performed all resulting negative.<ref name=\"loop-24april\" />\n\n==Preventive measures==\n* All schools are closed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://rcistlucia.com/covid-19-schools-closed/|title=Educational Institutions Closed from Monday 16th, 2020|website=RCI St Lucia|access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Non-essential businesses are closed.<ref name=\"nonessential\"/>\n* Curfew between 23:00 and 05:00.<ref name=\"29 March curfew\"/> Changed to 19:00 to 05:00 on 5 April.<ref name=\"ten_hour_curfew\"/>\n* Restaurants and bars are closed. [[Prohibition|Alcohol sales]] prohibited.<ref name=\"liquor\"/>\n* Airports are closed.<ref name=\"Case_3b\"/>\n* Limited reopening of minimarts and bakeries.<ref name=\"Shops open on limited basis\"/>\n\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"> </div>\n\n==Statistics==\nChronology of the number of active cases\n{{Graph:Chart\n| type = line\n| linewidth = 1\n| showSymbols = 1\n| yType= integer\n| width = 600\n| colors = #ff6347, cyan, black\n| xAxisTitle = Date\n| xAxisAngle = -40\n| xType = date\n| xAxisFormat = %e %b\n| x = 12 March 2020, 13 March 2020, 14 March 2020, 15 March 2020, 16 March 2020, 17 March 2020, 18 March 2020, 19 March 2020, 20 March 2020, 21 March 2020, 22 March 2020, 23 March 2020, 24 March 2020, 25 March 2020, 26 March 2020, 27 March 2020, 28 March 2020, 29 March 2020, 30 March 2020, 31 March 2020, \n1 April 2020, 2 April 2020, 3 April 2020, 4 April 2020, 5 April 2020, 6 April 2020, 7 April 2020, 8 A